<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-241-832  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 241 832.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  May 1 1989 v23 n18 p136(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Shareware: an alternative tool. (public domain software)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ruhl, Janet.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Corporate users are discovering the benefits of shareware, publicdomain software that is distributed freely among users.andP;  Sharewaredevelopers usually encourage the widespread copying of theprograms, depending on warranty registration and documentation fortheir incomes.andP;  Until recently, few corporate users risked theirapplications on what they considered shaky enterprises.andP;  However,shareware developers have created some sophisticated applicationsthat have perked corporate interests.andP;  After a trial period, userscan receive support at a cost far less than standard copyrightedprograms.andP;  Support is available either by telephone or throughuser groups that also act as independent distribution agents.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Public SoftwareFeature MeasurementCompaniesUser NeedsMarket PenetrationUser groups.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>